WORKS CITED CHECKLIST
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Before submitting, verify:

PAGE FORMAT:
☐ Works Cited is on its own page (page break after conclusion)
☐ "Works Cited" is centered at the top
☐ "Works Cited" is NOT bold, NOT underlined, NOT italicized
☐ Double-spaced throughout
☐ Entries are in alphabetical order

ENTRY FORMAT:
☐ Each entry uses hanging indent
☐ Author names are Last, First format
☐ Article titles are in "quotation marks"
☐ Website names are italicized
☐ Punctuation is correct (commas and periods in right places)
☐ Months are abbreviated (except May, June, July)
☐ Access dates are included and formatted correctly

CONTENT:
☐ Every in-text citation has a matching Works Cited entry
☐ Every Works Cited entry was actually cited in the essay
☐ All URLs are complete and correct

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SECTION 7: MECHANICS (10 Points)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

RUBRIC REQUIREMENTS FOR DISTINGUISHED (10/10):
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ • NO ERRORS in spelling, punctuation, or grammar                            │
│ • VARIED SENTENCE STRUCTURES                                                │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

SCORING BREAKDOWN:
Points | Requirements
-------|-------------
10     | No errors in spelling/punctuation/grammar, varied sentence structures
8      | Few minor errors, some sentence variety
6      | Noticeable errors slightly impacting readability, limited sentence variety
4      | Frequent errors significantly impacting readability, repetitive structures
2      | Numerous critical errors making comprehension difficult

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REQUIREMENT 1: SPELLING
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Zero tolerance for spelling errors at the Distinguished level.

========================
COMMONLY MISSPELLED WORDS IN ACADEMIC WRITING
========================

✓ DO spell correctly:
• definitely (NOT definately)
• separate (NOT seperate)
• occurrence (NOT occurence)
• beginning (NOT begining)
• government (NOT goverment)
• environment (NOT enviroment)
• argument (NOT arguement)
• receive (NOT recieve)
• achieve (NOT acheive)
• believe (NOT beleive)

========================
COMMONLY CONFUSED WORDS
========================

Spell-check will NOT catch these—memorize them:

THEIR / THERE / THEY'RE:
✓ DO: "Their earnings are higher." (possessive - belongs to them)
✓ DO: "There are many benefits." (location/existence)
✓ DO: "They're earning more money." (they are)

✗ DON'T: "There earnings are higher." (WRONG)
✗ DON'T: "Their are many benefits." (WRONG)

---

YOUR / YOU'RE:
✓ DO: "Your choice affects your future." (possessive)
✓ DO: "You're making an important decision." (you are)

✗ DON'T: "Your making an important decision." (WRONG)

Note: Academic writing avoids "you" entirely—but if you slip, get it right.

---

ITS / IT'S:
✓ DO: "College has its advantages." (possessive - no apostrophe!)
✓ DO: "It's important to consider all factors." (it is)

✗ DON'T: "College has it's advantages." (WRONG)
✗ DON'T: "Its important to consider..." (WRONG)

MEMORY TRICK: "It's" ALWAYS means "it is" — if you can't substitute "it is," use "its."

---

AFFECT / EFFECT:
✓ DO: "Education affects earnings." (verb - to influence)
✓ DO: "The effect is significant." (noun - the result)

✗ DON'T: "Education effects earnings." (WRONG - unless causing directly)
✗ DON'T: "The affect is significant." (WRONG)

MEMORY TRICK: Affect = Action (verb), Effect = End result (noun)

---

THAN / THEN:
✓ DO: "College graduates earn more than high school graduates." (comparison)
✓ DO: "Graduate first, then seek employment." (sequence)

✗ DON'T: "Earn more then high school graduates." (WRONG)

---

TO / TOO / TWO:
✓ DO: "Go to college." (direction)
✓ DO: "The cost is too high." (excessive/also)
✓ DO: "Two years of study." (number)

✗ DON'T: "The cost is to high." (WRONG)

---

LEAD / LED:
✓ DO: "This path leads to success." (present tense)
✓ DO: "This study led to important findings." (past tense)

✗ DON'T: "This study lead to findings." (WRONG - use "led")

========================
PROOFREADING STRATEGIES
========================

1. Read your essay backward (last sentence first)
   - Disrupts your brain's auto-correct
   - Helps you see each word individually

2. Read aloud
   - Your ear catches what your eye misses
   - Awkward phrasing becomes obvious

3. Use spell-check, but don't rely on it
   - Won't catch wrong word spelled correctly
   - Won't catch "their" when you meant "there"

4. Have someone else proofread
   - Fresh eyes catch more errors

5. Print and read on paper
   - Screen reading causes skimming
   - Paper forces slower reading

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REQUIREMENT 2: PUNCTUATION
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

========================
COMMA RULES
========================

RULE 1: After Introductory Elements

✓ DO:
"Despite the cost, college provides significant returns."
"According to research, graduates earn more."
"However, some students prefer trades."
"In today's economy, flexibility matters."

✗ DON'T:
"Despite the cost college provides significant returns."
→ Missing comma after introductory phrase

---

RULE 2: Before Coordinating Conjunctions in Compound Sentences

Coordinating conjunctions: for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so (FANBOYS)

✓ DO:
"College is expensive, but the investment pays off."
"Graduates earn more, and they have lower unemployment."
"Trades offer immediate income, yet long-term prospects differ."

✗ DON'T:
"College is expensive but the investment pays off."
→ Missing comma before "but"

Note: Only use comma if BOTH sides are complete sentences.

✓ NO comma needed: "Graduates earn more and have lower unemployment."
→ "have lower unemployment" is not a complete sentence by itself

---

RULE 3: Around Non-Essential Information

✓ DO:
"Trade schools, which offer hands-on training, appeal to some students."
"College, despite its cost, provides significant returns."
"The data, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, is clear."

✗ DON'T:
"Trade schools which offer hands-on training appeal to some students."
→ Missing commas around non-essential clause

---

RULE 4: In Lists (Serial/Oxford Comma)

✓ DO:
"College provides flexibility, higher earnings, and networking opportunities."
"Students consider cost, location, and program quality."

✗ DON'T:
"College provides flexibility, higher earnings and networking opportunities."
→ Missing comma before "and" (Oxford comma preferred in academic writing)

---

RULE 5: No Comma Between Subject and Verb

✗ DON'T:
"The evidence about college earnings, shows significant advantages."
→ Comma incorrectly separates subject from verb

✓ DO:
"The evidence about college earnings shows significant advantages."

========================
SEMICOLON RULES
========================

RULE 1: Between Independent Clauses Without Conjunction

✓ DO:
"College graduates earn more; this advantage compounds over time."
"The data is clear; higher education pays dividends."

Both sides must be complete sentences.

✗ DON'T:
"College graduates earn more; and higher earnings."
→ Second part is not a complete sentence

---

RULE 2: Before Conjunctive Adverbs

Conjunctive adverbs: however, therefore, moreover, consequently, furthermore

✓ DO:
"Trade work pays well initially; however, earnings plateau."
"The evidence is compelling; therefore, college remains valuable."
"Graduates have more options; furthermore, they experience lower unemployment."

✗ DON'T:
"Trade work pays well initially, however, earnings plateau."
→ Comma splice (use semicolon before, comma after)

========================
APOSTROPHE RULES
========================

RULE 1: Possessives (Singular)

✓ DO:
"The graduate's salary" (one graduate)
"The college's benefits" (one college)
"The worker's earnings" (one worker)

---

RULE 2: Possessives (Plural)

✓ DO:
"The graduates' salaries" (multiple graduates)
"Workers' earnings increase" (multiple workers)

Note: If the plural doesn't end in "s," add 's: "The children's futures"

---

RULE 3: NO Apostrophe for Plurals

✗ DON'T:
"College graduate's earn more." (WRONG - no possession)
"The 1980's saw changes." (WRONG - just a plural decade)

✓ DO:
"College graduates earn more." (simple plural)
"The 1980s saw changes." (plural decade)

---

RULE 4: "Its" (Possessive) vs "It's" (It Is)

✓ DO:
"College has its advantages." (possessive - no apostrophe)
"It's clear that college pays off." (it is)

✗ DON'T:
"College has it's advantages." (WRONG)

========================
PERIOD PLACEMENT WITH CITATIONS
========================

✓ DO:
"College graduates earn more (Bureau of Labor Statistics)."
→ Citation BEFORE the period

✗ DON'T:
"College graduates earn more. (Bureau of Labor Statistics)"
→ Citation should be inside the sentence

✗ DON'T:
"College graduates earn more (Bureau of Labor Statistics.)"
→ Period inside parentheses is wrong

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REQUIREMENT 3: GRAMMAR
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

========================
SUBJECT-VERB AGREEMENT
========================

✓ DO:
"The data show significant differences." (data is plural)
"The research indicates patterns." (research is singular)
"The number of graduates is increasing." (number is singular)
"A number of studies have shown..." (a number = many = plural)
"Each of the students has options." (each is singular)
"All of the evidence points to college." (evidence is singular)

✗ DON'T:
"The data shows significant differences." (data is plural)
"Each of the students have options." (each is singular)

========================
PRONOUN AGREEMENT
========================

✓ DO:
"A student should complete their work." (singular they - now acceptable)
"Students should complete their work." (plural)
"Each graduate has their own path." (singular they)

✗ DON'T (gendered assumptions):
"A student should complete his work."
"A graduate can improve his career."

Note: Singular "they" is now standard in academic writing when gender is unknown.

========================
VERB TENSE CONSISTENCY
========================

Use present tense for discussing research and general facts.

✓ DO:
"Research shows that graduates earn more."
"The data indicate significant patterns."
"College provides career flexibility."

✗ DON'T:
"Research showed that graduates earned more."
→ Past tense suggests the research is outdated

Exception: Use past tense for specific historical events:
"The 2008 recession affected employment rates."

========================
PARALLEL STRUCTURE
========================

Lists and comparisons must use the same grammatical form.

✓ DO:
"College provides higher earnings, greater flexibility, and broader skills."
(noun phrase, noun phrase, noun phrase)

"Graduates can earn more, advance faster, and adapt better."
(verb phrase, verb phrase, verb phrase)

✗ DON'T:
"College provides higher earnings, you get more flexibility, and skills are broader."
→ Inconsistent structures (noun, clause, clause)

"Graduates can earn more, faster advancement, and they adapt better."
→ Mixed structures

========================
DANGLING MODIFIERS
========================

✓ DO:
"After graduating from college, students often find better jobs."
→ "Students" is what graduated

"Considering the evidence, researchers conclude that college pays off."
→ "Researchers" is who considered

✗ DON'T:
"After graduating from college, better jobs are often available."
→ Jobs didn't graduate! (dangling modifier)

"Considering the evidence, college appears valuable."
→ College didn't consider! (dangling modifier)

========================
RUN-ON SENTENCES
========================

✗ DON'T:
"College is expensive students should still attend." (fused sentence)
"College is expensive, students should still attend." (comma splice)

✓ DO:
"College is expensive. Students should still attend." (two sentences)
"College is expensive, but students should still attend." (comma + conjunction)
"College is expensive; students should still attend." (semicolon)
"Although college is expensive, students should still attend." (subordination)

========================
SENTENCE FRAGMENTS
========================

✗ DON'T:
"Which is why college matters."
"Because graduates earn more."
"Such as earnings and flexibility."

✓ DO:
"This is why college matters."
"College matters because graduates earn more."
"Benefits include earnings and flexibility."

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REQUIREMENT 4: SENTENCE VARIETY
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The rubric specifically requires "varied sentence structures."

========================
THE FOUR SENTENCE TYPES
========================

1. SIMPLE SENTENCE (one independent clause):
"College graduates earn more."
"The data supports this conclusion."

2. COMPOUND SENTENCE (two independent clauses + conjunction):
"College requires investment, but the returns are substantial."
"Graduates earn more, and they experience lower unemployment."

3. COMPLEX SENTENCE (independent + dependent clause):
"Although trades offer immediate income, college provides superior long-term returns."
"Because career paths change frequently, flexibility proves valuable."

4. COMPOUND-COMPLEX SENTENCE (multiple clauses of both types):
"While some argue that trade school avoids debt, research shows that college graduates recover costs quickly, and they continue earning more throughout their careers."

========================
VARYING SENTENCE STRUCTURE - EXAMPLES
========================

✓ DO - Varied paragraph:

"College graduates consistently earn more over their lifetimes. [SIMPLE] According to federal data, the earnings gap exceeds $30,000 annually, and this difference compounds over a forty-year career. [COMPOUND] Although trade workers may earn more initially, college graduates surpass them by their mid-thirties. [COMPLEX] This crossover point matters significantly because workers typically have three decades of employment remaining, during which college graduates accumulate substantial additional wealth. [COMPLEX] The financial case for college is clear: short-term costs yield long-term gains. [SIMPLE with colon]"

What makes this effective:
✓ Mix of simple, compound, and complex sentences
✓ Different sentence lengths
✓ Varied sentence openings
✓ Smooth flow between ideas

✗ DON'T - Monotonous paragraph:

"College graduates earn more money. Trade workers earn less money. College provides more opportunities. Trade school provides fewer opportunities. College is the better choice. Trade school is not the better choice."

What's wrong:
• All simple sentences
• Same sentence pattern (Subject + verb + object)
• Same length sentences
• Same opening pattern
• Feels robotic and boring

========================
VARYING SENTENCE OPENINGS
========================

✓ DO - Vary how sentences begin:

"The evidence clearly demonstrates..." (subject first)
"According to federal data,..." (prepositional phrase)
"Although initial costs are high,..." (subordinate clause)
"Furthermore,..." (transitional word)
"By age 34,..." (prepositional phrase)
"Having examined the data,..." (participial phrase)

✗ DON'T - Same opening pattern:

"College graduates earn more."
"College graduates have more options."
"College graduates experience lower unemployment."
"College graduates adapt more easily."

→ Every sentence starts with "College graduates"

========================
VARYING SENTENCE LENGTH
========================

Mix short, medium, and long sentences.

✓ DO:
"The financial advantage is clear. [SHORT - 5 words] According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, workers with bachelor's degrees earn a median weekly salary of $1,432, compared to just $853 for those with only a high school diploma. [LONG - 32 words] This gap compounds over time. [SHORT - 5 words] Over a forty-year career, college graduates can expect to accumulate approximately $1.2 million more in total earnings than their peers who entered the workforce directly after high school. [LONG - 33 words] The numbers speak for themselves. [SHORT - 5 words]"

✗ DON'T - All same length:

"College graduates earn significantly more money than high school graduates according to data.
Workers with degrees have better job security and lower unemployment rates overall.
Career flexibility is another advantage that college education provides to graduates.
The evidence demonstrates that higher education is a worthwhile investment for most people."

→ Every sentence is ~15 words (monotonous)

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
REQUIREMENT 5: FORMAL ACADEMIC TONE
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

========================
AVOID CONTRACTIONS
========================

✗ DON'T:
don't → ✓ DO: do not
can't → ✓ DO: cannot
won't → ✓ DO: will not
it's → ✓ DO: it is
they're → ✓ DO: they are
there's → ✓ DO: there is
wouldn't → ✓ DO: would not
couldn't → ✓ DO: could not

========================
AVOID FIRST PERSON
========================

✗ DON'T:
"I think that college is the best choice."
"I believe students should attend college."
"In my opinion, the evidence is clear."
"We can see that graduates earn more."
"My argument is that college pays off."

✓ DO:
"Evidence suggests that college is the best choice."
"Students should consider attending college."
"The evidence clearly indicates..."
"The data show that graduates earn more."
"The argument presented here demonstrates..."

========================
AVOID SECOND PERSON
========================

✗ DON'T:
"You can earn more with a degree."
"Your career will benefit from college."
"If you want to succeed, you should attend college."

✓ DO:
"Workers can earn more with a degree."
"Careers benefit from college education."
"Students seeking success should consider college."

========================
AVOID INFORMAL LANGUAGE
========================

INFORMAL → FORMAL

"a lot of" → "numerous" or "significant"
"kind of" → "somewhat" or "to some degree"
"really" → "significantly" or "considerably"
"totally" → "completely" or "entirely"
"things" → "factors" or "elements" or "aspects"
"stuff" → "material" or "content" or "information"
"gets" → "receives" or "obtains" or "achieves"
"big" → "significant" or "substantial"
"good" → "beneficial" or "advantageous"
"bad" → "detrimental" or "adverse"
"okay" → "acceptable" or "adequate"
"a bunch of" → "numerous" or "many"

EXAMPLES:

✗ DON'T: "College is really important because of job stuff."
✓ DO: "College education proves essential for career advancement."

✗ DON'T: "You can earn a lot more money with a degree."
✓ DO: "Degree holders earn significantly more over their lifetimes."

✗ DON'T: "Getting a college degree is kind of hard but totally worth it."
✓ DO: "Pursuing a college degree presents challenges but yields substantial rewards."

========================
AVOID QUESTIONS IN ACADEMIC WRITING
========================

✗ DON'T:
"Why should students go to college?"
"Isn't it obvious that college is better?"
"What could be more valuable than education?"

✓ DO:
"Students benefit from college education."
"The value of college is clearly demonstrated."
"Education provides unmatched value."

========================
AVOID EXCLAMATION POINTS
========================

✗ DON'T:
"College is the best choice!"
"The evidence is overwhelming!"
"This is so important!"

✓ DO:
"College emerges as the superior choice."
"The evidence is compelling."
"This consideration is significant."

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
MECHANICS EXAMPLES AT DIFFERENT QUALITY LEVELS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

========================
DISTINGUISHED (10/10)
========================

"College graduates consistently earn significantly more over their lifetimes than those who enter the workforce directly after high school. According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, workers with a bachelor's degree earn a median weekly salary of $1,432, compared to $853 for those with only a high school diploma (Bureau of Labor Statistics). This gap of nearly $600 per week translates to over $30,000 in additional annual income. Although the initial investment in college requires financial commitment, the long-term returns substantially exceed the costs, demonstrating that higher education remains the most reliable path to financial security."

✓ No spelling errors
✓ No punctuation errors
✓ No grammar errors
✓ Varied sentence structures (simple, compound, complex)
✓ Formal academic tone throughout

========================
PROFICIENT (8/10)
========================

"College graduates earn more money then those who don't go to college. The Bureau of Labor Statistics shows that workers with degrees earn $1,432 per week (Bureau of Labor Statistics). This is a significant difference. Trade workers earn less and the gap gets bigger over time. College is worth the cost because you can earn more money in the long run."

Errors:
• "then" should be "than"
• "don't" is a contraction
• "gets" is informal
• "you" is second person
• Limited sentence variety (mostly simple sentences)

========================
BASIC (6/10)
========================

"College graduates earn alot more money. Studies show that there earning more. This effects their whole lifes. Its clear that college is better, if you want to succeed you should definately go. The evidence proves this conclusion, and everyone agrees its true."

Errors:
• "alot" → "a lot" (or "significantly more")
• "there" → "they're" or "they are"
• "effects" → "affects"
• "lifes" → "lives"
• "Its" → "It is" (contraction/wrong form)
• "you" → second person
• "definately" → "definitely"
• "its" → "it is"
• Run-on sentence
• Limited variety

========================
BELOW EXPECTATIONS (4/10)
========================

"College is good. College helps you. You can earn more. Trades are bad. Trades don't pay well. College is better then trades. You should go to college. College is important. I think college is the best."

Errors:
• Repetitive simple sentences
• Second person throughout (you)
• First person (I think)
• "then" → "than"
• Contraction (don't)
• No sentence variety at all
• Sounds like a list, not an essay

========================
NON-PERFORMANCE (2/10)
========================

"college is good you should go their are many benefits to college like money and jobs my opinion is college is definately better then trades if you dont go to college youll regret it"

Errors:
• No capitalization
• No punctuation
• Run-on sentence (entire passage)
• Multiple spelling errors
• Wrong word usage
• First and second person
• Contraction
• Comprehension is difficult

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
MECHANICS CHECKLIST
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Before submitting, verify:

SPELLING:
☐ No misspelled words
☐ Correct their/there/they're usage
☐ Correct your/you're usage
☐ Correct its/it's usage
☐ Correct affect/effect usage
☐ Correct than/then usage

PUNCTUATION:
☐ Commas after introductory elements
☐ Commas before coordinating conjunctions in compound sentences
☐ Semicolons used correctly between independent clauses
☐ Apostrophes only for possession and contractions
☐ No apostrophes in simple plurals
☐ Citations before periods

GRAMMAR:
☐ Subject-verb agreement
☐ Pronoun agreement
☐ Consistent verb tense (mostly present)
☐ Parallel structure in lists
☐ No dangling modifiers
☐ No run-on sentences
☐ No sentence fragments

SENTENCE VARIETY:
☐ Mix of simple, compound, and complex sentences
☐ Varied sentence openings
☐ Varied sentence lengths
☐ No repetitive patterns

FORMAL TONE:
☐ No contractions
☐ No first person (I, me, my, we)
☐ No second person (you, your)
☐ No informal language (a lot, kind of, stuff)
☐ No questions
☐ No exclamation points
